The Nigerian stock market last week sustained prior week bearish run as investors’ investment went down by N239 billion. The week, All-Share Index fell in four out of the five trading days to decline by 776.44 points or 2.69 per cent to close at 28,067.09 points. Similarly, investors lost N239 billion Week-on-Week (W-o-W) as market capitalisation dropped to N14.618 trillion. Of the five sub-sector gauges, four closed in red territory: the NSE Banking, NSE Oil/Gas, NSE Consumer Goods and NSE Industrial declined by 1.51 per cent, 3.05 per cent, 2.23 per cent and 4.07 per cent to close at 368.14 points, 243.89 points, 546.10 points and 1,180.26 points respectively. However, NSE Insurance rose by 0.23 per cent to close at 132.31 points. A total of 15 equities appreciated in price during the week, 49 equities depreciated in price, while 99 equities price remained unchanged. Law Union and Rock Insurance led the gainers table by 58.57 per cent to close at N1.11, per share. Union Bank of Nigeria (UBN) followed with a gain of 17.80 per cent to close at N6.95, while Honeywell Flour Mill rose by 17.80 per cent to close at N1.10, per share. On the other side, C & I Leasing led the decliners table by 26.53 per cent to close atN5.40, per share. Royal Exchange followed with a loss of 16.67 per cent to close at 25 kobo and Cadbury Nigeria declined by 16.28 per cent to close at N9.00, per share. Overall, a total turnover of 1.478 billion shares worth N20.295 billion in 23,263 deals were traded last week by investors on the floor of the Exchange, in contrast to a total of 1.561 billion shares valued at N26.073 billion that exchanged hands previous week in 21,444 deals. In the new week, analysts at Cowry Asset Management expected, “The local equities market to close slightly lower amid the rebound in Treasury Bills (T-bills) stop rates which was partly induced by the increase in Cash Reserve Ratio (CRR) by 500 basis points to 27.50 per cent. “Nevertheless, we advise investors to take advantage of the low prices to buy stocks with high dividend yields even at cheaper amounts.” Also, analysts at GTI Securities Limited noted that some earnings release has been impressive despite discouraging earnings report which has contributed largely to the negative sentiment in the equities market. Furthermore, Negative sentiments may persist into the first quarter as economic news is discouraging at the moment. “However, this will pose a good entry in form of dwindled stock prices into the second quarter as we are optimistic of corrective economic measures as the year goes by but still if more encouraging financial releases come on board, it should save the trading days.”